<TITLE> Retail investors boost share gains </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sep 1 (bdnews24.com)Bourses continued to close up Monday as a buying spree led almost 60 percent of traded scrips to secure gains. An official of brokerage house Lanka Bangla Securities told bdnews24.com that trading perked up as retail investors engaged in buying ahead of Eid. "It seems that retail investors have also acquired confidence on recent market gains," he added. Dhaka Stock Exchange's benchmark DGEN or general index maintained an upward curve across the day's trading, gaining 29.58 points, or 1.05 percent, to end on 2820.79. The DSI or all-share price index finished 18.59 points, or 0.77 percent, up at 2407.75. The blue-chip DSE-20 rose 11.50 points, or 0.47 percent, to close at 2453.03. Meanwhile, indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also closed upbeat paced by gains in non-bank financial institutions, mutual funds and energy shares. The CSCX or selective categories index advanced 59.91 points, or 1.05 percent, to close on 5727.47. The CASPI or all-share price index closed at 8768.42, climbing 92.09 points or 1.06 percent. The bourse's blue-chip CSE-30 crept up 6.69 points, or 0.08 percent, to end on 7898.79. Meanwhile, increased investor participation caused both turnover and trading volume to increase substantially from the previous day. Turnover on the DSE reached Tk 3.35 billionwith 17,719,159 shares changing handsup from Tk 2.66 billion the previous day. The port city bourse saw its turnover up to Tk 452.13 million, from Sunday's Tk 360.098 million, with 3,863,818 traded shares. Gainers outshined losers on the DSE by 141 to 76, while 10 issues held steady. On the CSE, 88 issues gained, 47 lost, and three remained unchanged. State-owned Titas Gas continued to top the turnover board on the DSE with a 3.03 percent gain from the previous day, closing at Tk 424.25. Second in line, ACI ended on Tk 524.70, advancing 3.57 percent. Beximco Pharma eroded Sunday's losses to climb 3.75 percent to Tk 113.40. Islami Bank finished at Tk 7576.75, down 2.80 percent after losing the previous day. Buying pressure led Lanka Bangla Finance to gain 3.22 percent, closing at Tk 224.20. Other scrips on the turnover boardDBH, British American Tobacco Bangladesh, ICB AMCL 2nd NRB mutual fund, Beximco and Square Pharmaceuticalsalso gained. bdn
